            'final_result': '## Segment Adjusted EBITDA: Construction and Why It Matters\n\n### 1. Definition (as disclosed in the S-1)\n\nThe filing defines **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** as **segment income (loss) from operations** excluding four items:\n\n1. **Depreciation and amortization**\n2. **Share-based compensation**\n3. **Restructuring charges**\n4. **Impairment**\n\nManagement states these measures are used "to assess our financial performance as well as for internal planning and forecasting purposes" and are presented to help investors "evaluate our operating performance and to compare the financial results." The filing also explicitly cautions that other companies "may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all, limiting their usefulness as comparative measures," and that the measures "should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for net income (loss), income (loss) from operations, or any other measure calculated in accordance with GAAP."\n\n### 2. Each Add-Back Relative to Segment Operating Income\n\nStarting from segment income (loss) from operations (the GAAP starting point), the four add-backs are:\n\n| Add-back | What it captures | Economic nature |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Depreciation & amortization** | Non-cash allocation of historical capex (launch vehicles, Starlink satellites, xAI compute infrastructure, acquired intangibles) | Real cash outflow occurred earlier; D&A is a proxy for prior-period capital intensity, not a "free" cost |\n| **Share-based compensation** | Equity granted to employees (heavily concentrated in the AI segment post-xAI merger) | Real economic cost via shareholder dilution; non-cash but recurring and dilutive |\n| **Restructuring charges** | Workforce reductions, lease exits, asset write-offs tied to reorganization (concentrated in AI segment, e.g., $487M in FY2025) | Episodic but reflects real cash and economic costs of reshaping the business |\n| **Impairment** | Write-downs of long-lived assets, goodwill, or investments (e.g., $3,775M in AI in FY2023; $38M in Space in FY2025) | Non-cash but signals prior over-investment or asset value deterioration |\n\nNote that Segment Adjusted EBITDA is **narrower** than the company-wide Adjusted EBITDA definition. Company-wide Adjusted EBITDA also excludes interest expense, interest income, other income (expense), and provision for income taxes — but those items sit below the segment line and therefore do not appear in the segment-level reconciliation.\n\n### 3. Why Understanding the Construction Matters Before Comparing Segment Economics\n\nThe four add-backs are **not symmetric across segments**, so naive comparison of Segment Adjusted EBITDA across Space, Connectivity, and AI can be highly misleading. Several issues stand out:\n\n**(a) Capital intensity is captured very differently across segments.** D&A is by far the largest add-back, and it is concentrated in the AI segment because of xAI\'s compute infrastructure build-out. In FY2025, D&A added back $3,568M to AI versus $2,376M to Connectivity and $757M to Space. Excluding D&A makes the AI segment\'s economics look far better than its cash consumption, because the underlying capex that generated that D&A was real cash spent in prior (and current) periods. An investor comparing Segment Adjusted EBITDA across segments without recognizing this would systematically overstate AI\'s relative profitability versus Space and Connectivity.\n\n**(b) Share-based compensation is heavily skewed to AI.** SBC added back $1,063M to AI in FY2025 versus $515M to Space and $369M to Connectivity. SBC is a real, dilutive economic cost. Excluding it flatters the AI segment disproportionately, especially because the recast consolidated entity includes xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) under common-control accounting — meaning the AI segment\'s SBC reflects equity-heavy compensation cultures imported from those entities.\n\n**(c) Restructuring and impairment are episodic and segment-specific.** Restructuring charges are essentially an AI-segment phenomenon ($487M in FY2025, $213M in FY2024, $237M in FY2023; zero in Space and Connectivity across all periods shown). Impairment is also lumpy — $3,775M in AI in FY2023 alone. Because these items are excluded, period-over-period Segment Adjusted EBITDA comparisons can mask large one-time economic events that genuinely affected segment value.\n\n**(d) The recast consolidated entity distorts historical comparability.** The S-1 retrospectively recasts all historical periods to include xAI and X Holdings under common-control accounting. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations. Segment Adjusted EBITDA for the AI segment in 2023–2024 therefore reflects xAI/X economics that did not exist within SpaceX at that time, and the Space and Connectivity segments\' historical figures may also reflect allocations that changed as a result of the recast. Comparing segment economics across years without understanding this recast basis can produce false trend signals.\n\n**(e) The metric excludes items that may be allocated inconsistently.** Segment Adjusted EBITDA starts from segment income (loss) from operations, which already reflects the company\'s internal cost-allocation methodology. Corporate-level items (interest, taxes, other income/expense) are excluded entirely. Two segments with identical Segment Adjusted EBITDA could have very different true economics once capital structure, tax position, and corporate overhead allocations are considered.\n\n**(f) Peer comparability is limited by construction differences.** The filing itself warns that peers "may calculate Adjusted EBITDA and Segment Adjusted EBITDA differently than we do or may not calculate them at all." A peer\'s "Adjusted EBITDA" may include or exclude different items (e.g., some peers add back transaction costs, litigation, or stock-based comp differently), so cross-company segment comparisons require line-by-line reconciliation rather than headline comparison.\n\n### 4. Illustrative Magnitude of the Distortion (FY2025)\n\n| Segment (FY2025, $M) | Operating income (loss) | Total add-backs | Segment Adjusted EBITDA | Add-backs as % of |op income| |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| Space | (657) | 1,310 | 653 | n/m (turns a loss into a profit) |\n| Connectivity | 4,423 | 2,745 | 7,168 | 62% |\n| AI | (6,355) | 5,118 | (1,237) | 81% of the loss is "added back" |\n\nThe AI segment\'s $6.4B GAAP operating loss is reduced to a $1.2B Segment Adjusted EBITDA loss — an $5.1B improvement driven overwhelmingly by D&A ($3.6B) and SBC ($1.1B). Without understanding that those add-backs represent prior capex and ongoing dilution, an investor could materially misjudge the AI segment\'s cash and economic burn rate relative to Space and Connectivity.\n\n### 5. Bottom Line\n\nSegment Adjusted EBITDA is a useful supplemental lens, but its construction — particularly the exclusion of D&A and SBC, which are large and unevenly distributed across segments — means it should never be used to rank segment economics without also examining:\n- segment-level capex and the cash conversion gap between D&A and actual capital spending,\n- segment-level SBC and its dilutive impact,\n- the episodic nature of restructuring and impairment by segment,\n- the common-control recast that makes historical AI segment figures non-standalone, and\n- the company\'s own cost-allocation methodology underlying segment operating income.\n\nThe filing\'s own cautionary language reinforces this: the measures "should not be considered in isolation or as a substitute for" GAAP operating income, and peer comparability is explicitly limited.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026 — Non-GAAP Measures (Adjusted EBITDA / Seg